title: For Sale/Trade:  Longbranch Lee Enfield No4 Mk1
postcontent:
I have an original Longbranch Lee Enfield No4 Mk1 from my collection I'm considering selling or trading. Chambered in the powerful and accurate .303 British round. The Canadian-made Longbranch Lee Enfields are considered by collectors to be the more collectible and better built Enfields of World War II.   

The bolt is a mis-match (common during re-arsenaling) but the metal on the rifle is in flawless condition.  The wood is Canadian maple and in original conditon (I've only conditioned in with linseed oil). This particular Enfield was part of a contingent of arms shipped to Egypt following World War II, and is noted by the Arabic script on the brass unit disk on the buttstock. Rifle has the period-correct micrometer sight which makes this rifle very accurate and will include a "pigsticker" bayonet.  It has been a safe queen along with the rest of my Enfields.

Offered for sale at $450 firm.  Definitely not in a rush to sell as these unaltered military surplus rifles are only increasing in value as time passes.  Please feel free to contact me with any questions.

title: For Sale:  1954 Chinese T53 Carbine with Bayonet, Mosin Nagant Variant
postcontent:
You will not find a nicer example for this price anywhere locally.

This is not a collectors item but a field ready weapon.

    I have a fully refinished 1954 Chinese Type 53 Carbine with Bayonet. 
This is the Chinese carbine copy of the very popular full size Russian Mosin Nagant also chambered 7.62 x 54R. This weapon came to me in fair to poor condition. I spent many hours slowly drawing the cosmoline out of the Chu wood and the steel of the rifle and bolt. I  hand sanded the wood down to a baby smooth 600 grit finish and painstakingly stained and sealed and then coated the stock with 6 individually sanded coats of polyurethane to give it a beautiful ( I think) deep red purple semi gloss finish and reassembled the rifle.
 The trigger has been lightened with new spring and shims. 
You'll have to take my word for it but the rifle had never been fired when I received it and I put one round through it just to ensure it functions properly. 
I have given it the "sticky bolt" treatment, polishing the bore and bolt assembly. 
The entire barrel, bore, trigger assembly and guard, butt plate, bayonet, etc. assembly of the rifle with the exception of the bolt assembly was re-blued. 
Comes with the wrench and I think I have a field kit somewhere too.

I have recently discovered skeet shooting and am separately selling this rifle and a Smith and Wesson 3000 12 gauge  pump to facilitate purchase of my first sporting shotgun. 

I also have available over 620 rounds of ammo, 440 still in spam can, for this weapon, at reasonable price.

Package deal for T53 and Ammo $250 obo.
In Kennesaw area, weekday meetings will have to be after 5pm.
Serious inquiry only, priced to sell.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 3000 12 gauge pump Police Barrel 2 3/4"
postcontent:
I have a Smith & Wesson Police barrel 12 gauge pump shot gun chambered 2 3/4". 
5 in the tube +1 in the chamber.
This was a police duty trade in I purchased a while back. 
I have been all through the action and have put around 50 rounds down the tube shooting trap and skeet. 
The rifle operated flawlessly and I would keep it for home defense but I  would like to get a purpose built sporting shotgun. 
Instead of re-bluing the barrel I hvlp sprayed it with a satin black enamel and baked it on. 
It looks nice and is durable as can be and will now stand up to all kinds of abuse. 
I have replaced the front bead.
It has a somewhat different style synthetic stock than I've seen on other examples and think it gives it a much meaner look.
Pics are low quality and were taken after reassembly from paint.

This rifle was patterned after Remington's very popular and reliable 870 model and I like shooting it better than the Mossberg 500 I once had. Some shotgun purists out there say it is a bastardized copy or somehow lower quality because S&W outsourced the manufacturing to Japan. I think it is of great quality for what it is and am only selling it to break in to sport shotgunning.
I am available weekdays after 5 pm, weekends are more open.
Asking $250.

Will include a external 5 shell sleeve that fits over the stock and 40 rifled slugs for an extra $20!

title: For Sale:  38 Acres for Bug-Out, Isolation and Gun Range
location: 15 Miles West of Laramie, Wyoming, United States
postcontent: Three lots of raw rural land for sale located 15 miles west of Laramie, Wyoming. Lot prices start at $48,500 for 38 acres and can be very negotiable for the right buyer (neighbor). Overhead or underground electric power is on some lots and can be brought in on lots where it is needed. Land is located on CR 44 (Big Hollow Road), 3 miles N/E of Lake Hattie, 6 miles east from National Forest and just east of Wild Horse Ranch. This land is ideal for those who want to park an RV or build a cabin and enjoy beautiful vistas with very few man made objects within miles. Personally, we are using it for a bug out when the SHTF along with being a nice retreat to target shoot and enjoy the solitude. We would be particularly interested in having like-minded neighbors that would appreciate a place to stock up and feel secure if/when the SHTF. We can build a cabin onsite using classic log building techniques .. our prototype cabin built last summer is shown in the pictures. We also have a sawmill and logs onsite, along with general construction equipment to get your property easily and economically usable for your particular needs. Please note that drilling for water is a hit and miss ordeal in this area, but you can easily haul your own water just like most everybody else living west of Laramie, or have it commercially delivered for $90 per 1500 gallons. The City of Laramie also has two high volume water dispensing depots designed for rural residents. One depot is in Laramie and the other depot is at the water treatment plant which is 10 miles from the property. Bottom line is, hauling water and a cistern holding tank is far more economical and feasible for a getaway cabin. Water well, casing and pump is estimated to be around $20K and that buys a lot of water at $.25/100 gallons at the depots.I am a licensed civil engineer and have lived in Laramie 30 years. I have a local Laramie phone number and address. If interested, shoot me an email and include your phone number so we can talk about being neighbors. All pictures, with the exception of the cabin picture and the "big valley" picture, are of the actual property available. The dirt road picture is of the private road that runs through the middle of the development. I look forward to hearing from you!

title: For Sale/Trade:  1923. Remington model 10-A, 26" barrel 12 ga, take down model
postcontent:
Made in November of 1923. Remington model 10-A, 26" barrel 12 ga, take down model. all numbers matching. Only 3500 of the 10-A were made. From what i have read, the 10-A models were used in WW2 by the USMC to train aerial gunners. However i see no ordnance stamps. For being 2 months short of it's 90th birthday this ol vet is in remarkable unrestored/ original condition. there is one small area of pitting on top of the receiver, but nothing too bad at all. It has 1 minor issue that prevents it from being used. A broken sear spring as seen in the pic below. It's a $10 part readily available online. The sear spring from a standard model 10 will interchange. This just isn't the shotgun for me so i'm not interested in restoring it, but would rather just trade it out for something i'll enjoy.

I am looking to trade for one of a couple of guns. In no special order i'd like an sks for the wife , a norinco in wood furniture is fine, she isn't picky at all. A Hi Point in .45 cal. only. I'd also like a single action 'cowboy gun' in .45 LC or .44 magnum. I'm not concerned about aesthetics, just that they cycle & fire properly.

The value as the 10-A sits now is $200-250 in the collectors circles. Restored and firing, $400. 

This was Remington's very first repeating shotgun. Introduced in 1908 and discontinued in 1929. This is an amazing piece of history & one any serious shotgun collector needs in their collection. 

I also want to ad this is a HUGE shotgun. In the pics below with me holding it, I'm 6'1" and 250lbs. I look like a kid holding 'daddys gun' ...lol. I picked this up last week & have decided it's just not the shotgun for me so i'm looking to trade out for something i will enjoy using. What do you have?
WILL TRADE FOR:

I am looking to trade for one of a couple of guns. In no special order i'd like an sks for the wife , a norinco is fine, she isn't picky at all.a Hi Point in .45 cal. only. The HP would need to come with ammo to help balance out the trade. I'd also like a single action 'cowboy gun' in .45 LC or .44 magnum. I'm not concerned about aesthetics, just that they cycle & fire properly.
